column63: Solar halo during greater part of the day
Lunar rainbow at 8 P.M. Full moon a few degrees above the horizon and rain in the west. Arch complete, but colors not perceptible.
First frost, except a little I think near the last of August
A little thunder in the evening, clouds from S.E.
Slight snow squalls – First snow of the season – The opposite shore or the north shore of the bay of Fundy, white
Aurora – commencing at 8 1/2 – arch very low, almost in horizon – streaming at 9
Aurora – first app– at 7 – arch very low – beams at 8 – no cloud below
Aurora – first observed at 9 – a fine arch a few degrees above horizon – dark cloud below
Aurora – commencing near end of twilight with clouds beneath – beams early developed – not remarkable
A mixture of rain and snow during the day from E.S.E. – about 1/2 inch of snow
Squalls of snow – blustering and cold
Commenced snowing about 11 P.M. and has continued until This the 30th at 9 P.M.  From W. and N.W.  Fall about 5 inches
Clouds (cirrus) from west most of the day, but becoming denser towards sunset. Between 7 and 8 P.M. wind shifts to E.S.E. with rain and frozen stuff,
Most of the month thus far. The sky has been cloudy, and slight falls of snow have accrued at intervals. Good sleighing ~
Rain – sleighing gone, and snow has nearly disappeared
Wind S.E. in afternoon and snows at 8 1/2, soon however becoming rain.
Violent wind from west with squalls of snow
Navigation closed in creek and river, until 25th when it opens again
A heavy fall of rain from the south
Snowstorms from NE. Commencing at night, but turning to rain at 1 1/2 P.M.
Heavy gales at 4 and 5 P.M. from SE with rain
Rain (Snowing or Raining most of the time it has been for several days
High wind last night from SE with rain – showery during day
A mild springlike day – wind W.S.W.
Very mild and springlike – frogs out – Snow mostly gone ~
Very mild and springlike – frogs out – Snow mostly gone ~
Very fair and springlike – Navigation open
A strong gale from SE to south with rain
Fine day – springlike – but little snow on ground
Very springlike – roads settled in some places – Navigation open – ice in bay nearly gone
Epigaea repens in bloom on southern exposure in a warm valley.
Showery – Hepatica Triloba in bloom in the above locality
Aurora  – Cold east wind several days
Ribums Americanus – Aurora – cloud below arch.
Fragaria virginiana in bloom in warm locality – also viola blanda
Depth of ground frozen one foot, much less than usual
Very fine – faint aurora – high arch
Cool – ice last night 1/8 of an inch thick
Thunder shower 4 P.M. from the west
Evening. Lightning in the north, about 20 miles distant, cloud moving to the east. Lightning zigzag and diffuse.
Lightning in evening in the N.W. Cloud moving to the N.E. Lightning diffuse.
Thunder storm passed a few miles to the south, between two and four P.M. moving to the S.E.
Lightning in N.W. in the evening, diffuse, very great distance off
Thunder storm came up about 2 1/2 PM from the S.W.
Evening, lightning in the SW, diffuse
Evening, Thunderstorm, cloud moving to N.E.
Between 9 and 11 o'c P.M. A great number of shooting stars, some very brilliant from all directions
Pnumerous meteors and shooting stars in the evening from all directions and making all angle with the horizon
Pnumerous meteors and shooting stars in the evening from all directions and making all angles with the horizon
Lightning in the evening in the N and NW. diffuse. shooting stars quite numerous
Shooting stars quite numerous in the evening. Some leaving brilliant streak visible some seconds  after the meteor its self had ceased to shine.
Aurora. Appeared about 8 o'c. At 9 o'c had the appearance of several arches of light one  with in the other with a very black [illegible] between them.

Magnificient aurora. A very fine exhibition of aurora occurred this evening. It commenced very soon after sunset and continued until midnight and perhaps longer. The sky was remarkably clear, and what was peculiar, the segment under the arch usually of a dark hue, was of a bright azure color, and so clear that stars in it were as distinctly visible as in other parts of the heavens
Slight Aurora - arch low, just above the horizon - few streamers
Aurora - occasional showers during evening so that it was not noticed till past
Frost last night for the first time this autumn in this place. Forty miles westward there was frost nearly a fortnight since.
A little rain today, but it is very dry
A few flakes of snow for the first time this autumn.
Very warm – frogs peeping in the evening – fine rain
Heavy rain again – clouds from N.E. – lower wind from the W
A lunar bow in the east or a little north of east – bright but exhibiting no prismatic colors – visible at a quarter to nine & remained so three quarters of an hour.
